     1	# Round 5 design — surgical-b: route evaluator versions; delete the baseline fast-out
     2	
     3	Status: final budgeted-round candidate. The complete normative design is the
     4	round-4 champion, `rounds/round-04/synthesis.md`, with exactly the two
     5	replacements in this file. No other round artifact is incorporated. All
     6	round-4 text not explicitly replaced below remains normative.
     7	
     8	Scope is intentionally closed to the round-5 docket: R1, R2, R3 (including
     9	A/B/A), R4, R8, R9, R12, and the merged fork-test list. The two judge
    10	blockers are repaired without a new mechanism: R1 generalizes the existing
    11	evaluator probe from “is staged?” to “does the cached flattened evaluator
    12	basis equal this world's effective versions?”, and R12's commit-baseline
    13	fast-out is deleted. Added state: none. Deleted state: two
    14	`commitBaseline` integers per root and their capture/lifecycle work.
    15	
    16	---
    17	
    18	## One page: the design that ships
    19	
    20	The inherited engine has nine cooperating mechanisms. K0 is the closed,
    21	packed donor kernel for the newest world. While a React bridge is registered,
    22	every atom write appends a receipt on a per-atom tape; a render world selects
    23	receipts by its immutable batch mask, global-sequence pin, and per-root lock
    24	view, then replays them in write order. K1 is a separate packed graph holding
    25	the real dependency edges discovered by non-newest evaluations. World memos
    26	store values plus a closed validity basis: slot write clocks, visibility
    27	stamps, exact flattened evaluator stamps, and the inherited suspense
    28	fingerprints. Watchers receive value-blind `setState` calls synchronously in
    29	the writer's execution context, so React supplies the writer's lanes.
    30	
    31	Hook evaluators and reducers are world-scoped. A render stages them under a
    32	lineage-stable stamp; F9 publishes only the hook version that actually becomes
    33	current. Committed evaluator versions sit on the same global sequence line as
    34	receipts, so an old pass resolves the version admitted by its pin. Round 4
    35	made memo validation version-aware but left the K0 routing gate version-blind:
    36	after K0 was recomputed under a newly promoted evaluator, an old pass could
    37	serve that K0 value before reaching the version-aware memo ladder. The repair
    38	uses the already-stored flattened evaluator vector as a mandatory exact
    39	precondition for every K0 serve and every fixup fast-out; no bit, clock, walk,
    40	or cache is added.
    41	
    42	The mount fixup closes the render-to-subscribe window. Its round-4
    43	`commitBaseline` optimization captured current committed currency immediately
    44	before layout, then mistook equality with that newly captured currency for
    45	proof that the earlier render used it. A retirement or cross-root promotion
    46	can occur after the mounting render but before that capture, when no watcher
    47	exists to receive the ordinary drain. The clean repair is deletion: after the
    48	existing structural fast-out and live-token entanglement loop, fixup always
    49	folds the current committed-for-root world and compares it with the rendered
    50	value. This withdraws the zero-`w_fx` in-transition-mount claim and charges the
    51	work to the existing mount gate; it removes state and a branch from F3.
    52	
    53	R2's pass-aware delivery, R3's lineage seeding and pre-commit restart, R4's
    54	durable drains, R8's discard-before-live-renumber, and R9's per-world atom
    55	identity survive adversarial re-derivation below. The fork remains nine
    56	versioned facts, tests 1–33 remain the merged suite, and the two new attacks
    57	are pinned as integration tests rather than new seam facts. DIRECT mode is
    58	unchanged and executes zero concurrency instructions. The repaired design has
    59	no unwalked docket case and no new correctness gap.
    60	
    61	---
    62	
    63	## Terms used in this amendment
    64	
    65	- **Global sequence (`seq`)**: the monotone integer line shared by writes,
    66	  retirements, evaluator promotions, render pins, and committed-advance
    67	  stamps. Comparisons across these events are meaningful because they use one
    68	  line.
    69	- **Batch token / slot / mask**: React gives each live batch a stable integer
    70	  token. The library interns at most 31 live-or-unswept tokens into slots; a
    71	  pass mask names the batches it renders.
    72	- **World**: an immutable view header containing a root, pass mask, pin, and
    73	  immutable per-root lock view. A receipt is visible when its retirement is at
    74	  or below the pin, its live slot is in the pass mask and its write is at or
    75	  below the pin, or its slot is in the root's lock view and its write is at or
    76	  below that slot's watermark.
    77	- **K0 / K1**: K0 is the canonical newest-world signal graph. K1 is the union
    78	  of real dependency edges recorded by non-newest evaluations. K1 does not
    79	  alter K0's hot traversal records.
    80	- **Canonical-trust (`CT`)**: the inherited freshness predicate that says a
    81	  K0 value can be served without recomputation. It is necessary but, for a
    82	  pass world, not sufficient.
    83	- **Touched word**: the inherited per-node slot/taint reach word. It routes
    84	  receipt-sensitive reads and feeds durable per-slot touched lists. It is not
    85	  the value-blind notification walk.
    86	- **Evaluator**: a `useComputed` function or reducer whose identity can change
    87	  with hook deps. A staged evaluator belongs to a render lineage until F9
    88	  publishes it. A committed evaluator version is
    89	  `{fn, deps, stamp, promotedAtSeq}`.
    90	- **Effective evaluator**: for a pass world, the pass's staged version when
    91	  present, otherwise the committed version with greatest
    92	  `promotedAtSeq <= world.pin`; for NEWEST and committed-for-root reads, the
    93	  latest committed version.
    94	- **Evaluator basis**: the exact flattened vector of `(evaluator, stamp)`
    95	  pairs consumed to produce a cached value. Each stageable evaluation records
    96	  its own pair before invoking user code and merges child vectors. The vector
    97	  already exists for memo validity and suspense content validity.
    98	- **World memo**: the per-`(node, worldKey)` cached value and its validity
    99	  basis. Atom folds use this same plane, so one atom has one reference in one
   100	  world.
   101	- **Watcher**: a mounted component subscription. Its notification is a
   102	  synchronous `setState` in the writer's context.
   103	- **Fixup (`w_fx`)**: the layout-time render-to-subscribe check. It first
   104	  entangles live batches that the mount may have missed, then compares the
   105	  rendered value with the current committed-for-root value and schedules an
   106	  urgent pre-paint correction if they differ.
   107	- **Lineage**: the fork identity stable across retries/replays of one root and
   108	  batch selection. Its stage cache lets a retry see staged evaluators before
   109	  tree-order-late owner hooks run.
