   112	
   113	## Normative replacement S5-R1 — evaluator versions participate in routing
   114	
   115	This extends round-4 R1; its pin-gated version chain, retention rule,
   116	promotion ordering P1′–P4, value-blind promotion walk, RENDER_NEWEST
   117	demotion, and memo/capsule validity checks remain unchanged.
   118	
   119	For the current K0 cached value of node `n`, let `B0(n)` be its existing
   120	flattened evaluator basis. Define the following predicate as math, not a new
   121	stored flag:
   122	
   123	```text
   124	EB0(n, w) := for every (e, stamp) in B0(n),
   125	             effectiveStamp(e, w) == stamp
   126	```
   127	
   128	Let `B_r(n, w_r)` be the basis of the exact cached result the render served:
   129	`B0(n)` when it served K0, otherwise the basis of `M(n, w_r)`. Define:
   130	
   131	```text
   132	EBr→c(n, w_r, w_c) := for every (e, stamp) in B_r(n, w_r),
   133	                      effectiveStamp(e, w_c) == stamp
   134	```
   135	
   136	Both are exact vector walks; there is no lossy hash and no allocation. The
   137	normative routing changes are:
   138	
   139	1. A pass-world read may serve K0 only if all inherited K0 gates hold **and
   140	   `EB0(n, world)` holds**. Test this before returning K0, not after entering
   141	   the world-memo ladder. A mismatch routes to the existing world evaluation.
   142	2. The staged-only routing probe is replaced by this effective-version probe.
   143	   A stage, a pin-resolved superseded committed version, and a nested
   144	   evaluator therefore use one rule.
   145	3. The mount fixup's initial structural fast-out may return only if its
   146	   inherited conditions hold **and `EBr→c(n, w_r, committedForRoot(now))`
   147	   holds**. The pass retains the cache/basis it served through layout under
   148	   the inherited pass-owned memo lifetime; this adds no watcher field. A
   149	   version change in the render-to-subscribe window must reach the final
   150	   `w_fx` compare.
   151	4. Every world memo still checks its own flattened evaluator basis before
   152	   clocks or value serve. Promotion still dirties K0, demotes open
   153	   RENDER_NEWEST passes, and performs the unconditional value-blind walk.
   154	
   155	No new completeness obligation is introduced: evaluator-basis flattening is
   156	already required by I31/I40 and round-4 R1 for memo and suspense validity.
   157	This amendment merely consults that same exact basis one decision earlier.
   158	
   159	### S5-R1-A pinned attack: recomputed K0 leaks a post-pin evaluator
   160	
   161	Setup: shared stageable reducer atom `ra`; committed reducer `r0` maps
   162	`inc` to `+1`, staged reducer `r1` maps it to `+10`; receipt X contains
   163	`inc`. Root B renders siblings B1 and B2 from X-world. Root A owns the hook
   164	that can publish `r1`.
   165	
   166	```text
   167	step | actor/mechanism | state touched (values, bases, lanes)
   168	1 | root-B pass P starts | pin=q; mask={X}; effective reducer=r0
   169	2 | B1 reads ra | fold under r0 => 1; B1 renders 1; P yields
   170	3 | root A F9 publishes r1 | promotedAt=sA>q; K0 dirtied; open P demoted; value-blind walk schedules B; no equality gate
   171	4 | NEWEST read on A | K0 recomputes ra under r1 => 10; K0 becomes CT with B0(ra)={(ra,r1)}
   172	5 | P resumes and B2 reads ra | EB0 compares effectiveStamp(ra,P)=r0 with cached r1 => mismatch; route existing world memo; fold X under r0 => 1
   173	6 | P commits | B1=1 and B2=1; queued publication delivery later renders both under r1 => 10
   174	outcome: the old pass cannot serve the recomputed K0 value; every committed frame uses one reducer version.
   175	residual risk: omitting the probe at any K0-return site reopens the leak; integration test S5-R1-A instruments every K0 serve and forces step 4.
   176	```
   177	
   178	Without rule 1, step 5 returns 10 because `touched==0` and K0 is clean; the
   179	version-aware memo ladder is never entered. That is the judge's R1 blocker.
   180	
   181	### R1 construction
   182	
   183	Base case: with no staged or superseded evaluator, every recorded basis pair
   184	resolves to the sole committed stamp. `EB0` holds, so the inherited K0 gates
   185	decide exactly as before.
   186	
   187	Inductive step for a stage: staging changes `effectiveStamp` in that pass.
   188	The node records its own evaluator pair before user code, and every parent
   189	that consumes it merges the pair; therefore the first cached node whose value
   190	could depend on the stage has a mismatching pair and routes. R3 restarts any
   191	watcher that rendered before the stage was minted.
   192	
   193	Inductive step for a promotion: consider the two possible K0 bases. If K0 is
   194	still based on the old version, a pre-promotion pass matches and is safe;
   195	NEWEST/latest worlds mismatch or see P2′ dirtiness and recompute. If K0 has
   196	been recomputed under the new version, latest worlds match and every pass
   197	pinned before promotion mismatches and world-routes. Flattening applies the
   198	same argument transitively to a parent cache. Thus replacing either K0 basis
   199	cannot make an incompatible world satisfy the exact predicate.
   200	
   201	Equal output does not weaken the argument: evaluator stamp identity, not
   202	value equality, controls routing, and promotion delivery remains value-blind.
   203	
